'''''Thelypodium eucosmum''''' is a species of flowering plant in the [[Brassicaceae|mustard family]] known by the common names '''arrow-leaf thelypody''' and '''world thelypody'''. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Oregon]] in the United States, where it is known from [[Grant County, Oregon|Grant]] and [[Wheeler County, Oregon|Wheeler Counties]].<ref name=cpc>[http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/Collection/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=4274 ''Thelypodium eucosmum''.] Center for Plant Conservation.</ref> There are also historical records of the plant from [[Baker County, Oregon|Baker County]].<ref name=or>[http://www.oregon.gov/ODA/PLANT/CONSERVATION/profile_theu.shtml ''Thelypodium eucosmum''.] Oregon Department of Agriculture.</ref>

This species is a biennial or short-lived perennial herb. It produces an erect, branching stem which can reach a meter in height. The basal leaves are lance-shaped or sometimes oval in shape and are borne on a short [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]]. The leaves higher on the stem are smaller and have no petiole.<ref name=fna>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=250094925 ''Thelypodium eucosmum''.] Flora of North America.</ref> They may clasp the stem<ref name=or/> or may be arrowhead-shaped, with projections extending around the stem. The [[inflorescence]] is a [[raceme]] of many flowers with purple petals. The fruit is a [[silique]] up to 6.5 centimeters long.<ref name=fna/>

This species occurs in the [[Blue Mountains (Oregon)|Blue Mountains]] of Oregon, and along [[tributary|tributaries]] of the [[John Day River]].<ref name=ns>[http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/servlet/NatureServe?searchName=Thelypodium+eucosmum ''Thelypodium eucosmum''.] NatureServe.</ref> Its habitat is dominated by [[Artemisia tridentata|sagebrush]] and [[Juniperus occidentalis|juniper]]. It grows in moist areas such as river canyons and streambanks.<ref name=cpc/><ref name=ns/> The plant's population size is greatly affected by the availability of water.<ref name=ns/> Other plants in the habitat may include ''[[Balsamorhiza]]'' spp., ''[[Bromus mollis]]'', ''[[Bromus tectorum|B. tectorum]]'', ''[[Ericameria nauseosa]]'', ''[[Gutierrezia sarothrae]]'', ''[[Hordeum murinum]]'', ''[[Lepidium]]'' spp., ''[[Purshia tridentata]]'', ''[[Salix]]'' spp., ''[[Sarcobatus vermiculatus]]'', and ''[[Urtica dioica]]''.<ref name=or/>

[[Grazing]] is a main threat to the species; some populations have been [[local extinction|extirpated]] by livestock grazing.<ref name=ns/>

